        <section>
            <div id="faqs" class="row">
                <h3 class="h3-title">FREQUENTLY ASKED</h3>
                <h2 class="h2-title">QUESTIONS</h2>
                <div class="col-md">
                    <p class="faqs-questions">Q. How do I know if counseling is for me?</p>
                    <p class="faqs-answers">A. Counseling is not exclusive to anyone although, the process may vary with each individual. It is for anyone facing a short term or a long-standing difficulty emotionally or psychologically and is willing to process/ develop skills to regulate their emotional state. Taking a session could help with analyzing if one feels the need for it.</p>
                    
                    <p class="faqs-questions">Q. How long is the session?</p>
                    <p class="faqs-answers">A. A session is usually 50-55 minutes long, though the in-take session can sometimes be longer.</p>
                    
                    <p class="faqs-questions">Q. What are the things I need to be clear about before reaching out to a therapist?</p>
                    <p class="faqs-answers">A. There are a couple of things you should have clarity over before you reach out to a therapist. Firstly, you need to be clear about your motivation and willingness to commit to the process considering it will take time. Secondly, what is it that I want to achieve from therapy? Apart from that, are you willing to continue long enough to see results?</p>
                    
                    <p class="faqs-questions">Q. How do I know if a particular therapist is right for me?</p>
                    <p class="faqs-answers">A. I suggest talking to your therapist before you sign up, it gives some clarity on whether you can work with them. Someone can be a great therapist and still not be fit for you.</p>
                    
                    <p class="faqs-questions">Q. What are your qualifications?</p>
                    <p class="faqs-answers">A. I've completed MS Clinical and Counseling Psychology from Beaconhouse National University Lahore and have been practicing for over two years.</p>

                    <p class="faqs-questions">Q. How much does a session cost?</p>
                    <p class="faqs-answers">A. I take Rs. 3000/- per session.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="col-md">
                    <p class="faqs-questions">Q. How many session does one need?</p>
                    <p class="faqs-answers">A. Usually, 8-12 sessions are required but it depends on the problem one is facing and the need for assistance. Usually, a session weekly is scheduled initially and then as progress takes place we can move towards spacing them out.</p>

                    <p class="faqs-questions">Q. What is your professional qualification?</p>
                    <p class="faqs-answers">A. I have done my Masters in Clinical and Counseling Psychology.</p>

                    <p class="faqs-questions">Q. How do I book a session?</p>
                    <p class="faqs-answers">A. You can call me, email me or reach out to me through my Instagram account provided in the contact details on the website. I offer a 15-minute free consultation over a call to discuss what you want to seek therapy for, if I am fit for it and when can we book an appointment.</p>
                    
                    <p class="faqs-questions">Q. What happens in the in-take session?</p>
                    <p class="faqs-answers">A. In the intake session I normally try to assess the complaints my clients bring to therapy and screen for the factors that might be playing a major role in maintaining the problem one is facing. It is usually a thorough conversation about the difficulties one is facing and a general assessment.</p>

                    <p class="faqs-questions">Q. Does taking therapy mean I get diagnosed with a mental disorder?</p>
                    <p class="faqs-answers">A. Not necessarily, as I have mentioned before therapy is for anyone and everyone and while diagnosis holds therapeutic importance and helps with designing the treatment protocol, I prefer to not focus entirely on it unless my clients need me to. As a mental health professional, I also aspire to reduce stigma around seeking help for one's mental health and unfortunately sometimes diagnosis can be counter-productive.</p>
                </div>
